; confidence-calibrate.form — map a raw recognition strength to a calibrated bucket, so "70" means the same trust everywhere.
;
; THE PLACE IN THE SPINE:
;   feature-vector.form bins a WINDOW of readings into a histogram; recognition-router.form routes
;   the CONFIDENCE VECTOR a model already produced. This is the one-value sibling of the histogram:
;   a single raw strength 0..100 binned into one calibrated level. Raw strengths are not comparable
;   across models — one model's 70 is timid, another's 70 is brash — but a bucket cut by SHARED
;   ascending thresholds is. So "70" stops meaning "whatever this model felt" and starts meaning a
;   fixed level of trust the router, the fuser, and the human all read the same way. Models are DATA
;   upstream; the calibration is Form, kernel-native, three-way-identical — the same score yields the
;   same bucket on the Mac and the phone, a content-addressed substrate cell verifiable by NodeID.
;
; THE SHAPE  (runnable: form-stdlib/confidence-calibrate.fk · proven: tests/confidence-calibrate-band.fk -> 127)
;
;   cc-bucket (score thresholds) -> bucket index
;     how many ascending thresholds the score meets-or-exceeds. Recurse the thresholds, +1 per
;     (ge score threshold). Below all -> 0; at-or-above the last -> k. The boundary is ge, not gt:
;     a score equal to a threshold belongs to the HIGHER bucket. This is feature-vector's fv-bin
;     exactly — inlined here, not called, per AUTHORING's self-contained rule (a band preludes only
;     this recipe + core, so every function it touches lives in this file). The bucket IS the
;     calibration: it composes the same content-addressed spine as the histogram bin upstream.
;
;   cc-level (score thresholds) -> "low" | "mid" | "high"
;     a thin NAME for the bucket so a human reads trust at a glance: bucket 0 -> "low", bucket 1 ->
;     "mid", every higher bucket -> "high". Nested binary if — and/or are binary in this primitive
;     set, so a three-way choice is two stacked ifs, never a flat cond. The name is a reading of the
;     bucket, never a second source of truth; change the thresholds and both the bucket and its name
;     move together.
;
;   cc-trusted? (score floor) -> 0 | 1
;     a single proven-count gate — does the score clear the trust floor (ge, meets-or-exceeds). No
;     ratio, no mean, no float: the same proven-count rule classifier-eval.fk and recognition-router's
;     rr-trusted? ride. Returns 0/1 explicitly because a bare comparison's boolean shape diverges
;     across kernels (Go/Rust/TS represent it differently), so it is wrapped to an integer the band
;     can `eq` — the body-state.fk lesson, carried.
;
; HOW IT COMPOSES THE SPINE:
;   feature-vector (make the vector) -> a classifier emits a raw strength -> confidence-calibrate
;   (calibrate that strength to a shared bucket) -> recognition-router (route/fuse the now-comparable
;   confidences). Same thresholds + same score => same bucket everywhere, so two models calibrated
;   against one threshold list become directly comparable: the router's "highest strength wins" is
;   only honest once the strengths share a scale, and this is where they get it. A declared reading
;   (declared-source.form) skips the classifier and arrives calibrated to 100 for free.
;
; HONEST LANE / CAVEAT:
;   This calibrates the SCALE, not the model. It makes a 70 mean the same level of trust across
;   models; it does NOT make a model's 70 correct. A confidently-wrong classifier calibrates to
;   "high" and is high-confidence wrong — calibration aligns the ruler, it does not measure truth.
;   The thresholds are the designer's choice, supplied as data, not learned here; bad thresholds make
;   a consistent-but-useless bucketing (every score collapses to one level). The score is assumed an
;   integer 0..100 on the same exact-comparison ground the rest of the spine rides — no float, no
;   negative. Whether a 70 DESERVES trust is grounded elsewhere (self-grounding against declared
;   ground truth); this recipe only guarantees that wherever a 70 appears, it is the same 70.
;
; KIN: feature-vector.form (the histogram this is the one-value bucket of) · recognition-router.form
;      (routes the calibrated confidences) · declared-source.form (a declared reading is calibrated
;      to 100 for free) · turboquant-as-recipe (the data-oblivious quantization both this and the
;      histogram instance) · value-execution.fk (count/gate only what clears the bar) ·
;      the three-way validate.sh (no trusted prover — parallel kernels, what survives the agreement).